    story: `<p>Nepal's adventure tourism scene was transformed in 1999 when The Last Resort opened the country's first commercial bungee jump above the Bhotekoshi River canyon in Sindhupalchok district. The site was chosen for its extraordinary natural drama: a narrow suspension bridge spans a gorge where the turquoise Bhotekoshi River roars 160 metres below, flanked by sheer cliffs draped in subtropical vegetation. Within a few years it had earned a reputation as one of the top ten bungee experiences in Asia.</p><h3>The Jump Experience</h3><p>Jumpers are fitted into a full-body harness on the wooden suspension bridge before stepping off into a near-vertical free-fall that lasts roughly four seconds. The rebound swings participants out over the gorge in a series of oscillations before a trained crew slowly winches them back to the bridge. The resort also offers a swing (canyon swing), white-water rafting on the Bhotekoshi, and multi-day tented camps, making it a full adventure destination rather than a single-activity stop.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>160-metre free-fall from historic suspension bridge</li><li>Canyon swing option for those who prefer a pendulum arc</li><li>Gorge-side tented camp accommodation available</li><li>Certified by international bungee safety standards</li><li>3–4 hour drive from Kathmandu on the Arniko Highway toward Tibet</li></ul>`,
