    name: "Rock Climbing Nagarjun Forest",
    category: "ADVENTURE_SPORTS",
    summary: "The limestone cliffs inside Nagarjun Forest Reserve, just 5 km from central Kathmandu, host more than 21 bolted sport-climbing routes on a dramatic 55-metre wall near the Balaju Quarry. Routes range from beginner-friendly slabs to overhanging test-pieces, making it Nepal's most accessible natural outdoor climbing venue. Certified guides and equipment rental are available on-site, and the dense forest setting provides welcome shade year-round.",
    story: `<p>Rock climbing as a recreational sport in Nepal is anchored by the crags at Nagarjun Forest Reserve, which have served as the training ground for Nepali climbers and a convenient day-out for visiting mountaineers for over two decades. The main crag, near the Balaju Quarry entrance, presents a solid limestone wall rising 55 metres above the forest floor, split into three distinct sectors. Pioneer route developers bolted more than 21 lines, ensuring sport climbers can move between grades comfortably without trad gear.</p><h3>The Climbing</h3><p>The Balaju Quarry sector features both vertical face routes and overhanging crimpy lines suited to intermediate and advanced climbers. A slab sector on the right side of the wall offers gentler angles ideal for beginners learning movement technique. Most routes are 20–55 m, and top-rope setups can be rigged at the bolted anchors for those in instruction. Several Kathmandu climbing schools use the crag weekly for training sessions and introductory courses.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>21+ bolted sport routes on 55-metre limestone cliff</li><li>Grades ranging from beginner slabs to advanced overhangs</li><li>Only 5 km (20-minute drive) from Thamel, Kathmandu</li><li>Forest setting with shade and natural ambiance</li><li>Guided climbing and equipment hire available from Kathmandu operators</li><li>Entry fee: NPR 250 for foreigners</li></ul>`,
