    summary: "Janakpur, the capital of Madhesh Province, is one of the holiest cities in the Hindu world, revered as the birthplace of Goddess Sita and the ancient capital of the kingdom of Mithila. The city is studded with more than 70 ponds, numerous temples, and the magnificent Janaki Mandir, and pulses with Maithili culture expressed through traditional Mithila painting, festivals like Vivah Panchami, and the unique Janakpur Women's Development Centre. Located about 225 km southeast of Kathmandu, it draws pilgrims from across Nepal and India.",
    story: `<p>According to Hindu tradition, Janakpur was the capital of King Janak's kingdom of Mithila during the Treta Yuga, the era of the Ramayana epic. It was here that King Janak discovered the infant Sita in a ploughed furrow of a field and raised her as his daughter; the city's ponds, known as kunds, are said to have been used for her childhood play and ritual bathing. The site was rediscovered in 1657 by the saint Shurkishordas, who found a golden statue of Sita at the spot now occupied by the Janaki Mandir.</p><h3>Sacred Ponds and Temples</h3><p>Janakpur is called the City of Ponds for its 72 sacred tanks, the largest being Ganga Sagar Kund. The city contains dozens of temples dedicated to Ram, Sita, Hanuman, and Shiva, and the annual Vivah Panchami festival—celebrating Ram and Sita's wedding—draws hundreds of thousands of pilgrims each November. The narrow-gauge Janakpur Railway, one of Nepal's oldest, still connects the city to the Indian border at Jaynagar.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Janaki Mandir – ornate marble temple of Goddess Sita</li><li>72 sacred ponds including Ganga Sagar Kund</li><li>Mithila painting tradition visible on homes and at the Women's Development Centre</li><li>Vivah Panchami festival (November) – one of Nepal's largest pilgrimages</li><li>Janakpur Railway heritage narrow-gauge line to Indian border</li><li>UNESCO tentative World Heritage Site (Ram Janaki Temple, 2008)</li></ul>`,
