    name: "Janaki Mandir",
    category: "TEMPLE",
    summary: "The Janaki Mandir in Janakpur is a breathtaking three-storied marble and stone temple dedicated to Goddess Sita (Janaki), built in 1910 by Queen Vrisha Bhanu of Tikamgarh and considered one of Nepal's most magnificent religious structures. Constructed in Koiri Hindu architectural style with 60 rooms, ornate turrets, Madhubani paintings, and lattice windows, the temple marks the very spot where a golden statue of Sita was discovered in 1657. It is a UNESCO tentative World Heritage Site and one of the most important pilgrimage destinations in the Hindu world.",
    story: `<p>The Janaki Mandir stands on the sacred ground where, according to tradition, King Janak discovered the infant Sita and where she spent her childhood in the ancient Mithila kingdom. In 1657, the saint Shurkishordas unearthed a golden statue of Sita at this precise location, and a small shrine was established. Two and a half centuries later, Queen Vrisha Bhanu of Tikamgarh in central India financed the construction of the present grand temple, completed around 1910 at a cost of nine lakhs of rupees—earning it the popular name Nau Lakha Mandir.</p><h3>Architecture and Interiors</h3><p>The temple covers 1,480 square metres and rises through three stories of gleaming white stone and marble. Its 60 rooms are decorated with traditional Madhubani (Mithila) paintings and coloured glass engravings. The outer walls are adorned with intricate relief carvings and lattice windows, while dozens of small turrets rise to a central spire. Inside the inner sanctum, a flower-garlanded image of Sita is enshrined alongside Ram and Lakshman; the mandapa (pavilion) attached to the temple is believed to be the site of the legendary Swayamvara ceremony where Sita chose Ram as her husband.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Nau Lakha Mandir – built at cost of nine lakhs by Queen Vrisha Bhanu, 1910</li><li>Three-storied marble and stone Koiri Hindu architecture</li><li>60 rooms with Madhubani paintings and coloured glass</li><li>Believed site of Ram-Sita Swayamvara ceremony</li><li>UNESCO tentative World Heritage Site since 2008</li><li>Vivah Panchami celebrations draw hundreds of thousands of devotees</li></ul>`,
