    name: "Saptakoshi River",
    category: "RIVER",
    summary: "The Saptakoshi (Kosi River) is one of Nepal's mightiest rivers, formed by seven Himalayan tributaries and carrying immense volumes of water through eastern Terai before entering India. The river system supports over 134 native fish species including the prized Golden Mahseer, making it a premier destination for sport fishing, while its extensive wetlands and sandbars host more than 485 bird species. The Koshi Barrage and the floodplains around Koshi Tappu Wildlife Reserve are the most rewarding stretches for naturalists and anglers.",
    story: `<p>The Saptakoshi is born from seven major Himalayan rivers—the Sun Koshi, Tamor, Arun, Dudh Koshi, Bhote Koshi, Indrawati, and Tama Koshi—that converge near the Tribeni confluence in eastern Nepal before the combined river cuts through the Siwalik Hills at the Koshi Gorge and spreads across the Terai. The name Saptakoshi literally means 'seven Koshis', and the river's legendary floods have historically made it both a bringer of life and a fearsome force—it is sometimes called the Sorrow of Bihar for its tendency to shift course and inundate vast areas.</p><h3>Fishing and Wildlife</h3><p>The river's clear cold upper reaches near the Koshi Gorge and the tributary confluences at Mai Beni and Triveni are renowned for Golden Mahseer (Tor putitora) and Goonch catfish, drawing fly fishermen from around the world between October and April. Downstream, the Koshi Tappu Wildlife Reserve preserves the river's floodplain ecology, sheltering Nepal's last wild water buffalo, gharial crocodiles, and an extraordinary diversity of migratory waterbirds that use the Koshi as a flyway corridor between Central Asia and the Indian Subcontinent.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Seven tributaries creating one of Asia's most biodiverse river systems</li><li>Golden Mahseer and Goonch fishing at Mai Beni and Triveni</li><li>485 bird species including large adjutant stork, Pallas's fish eagle</li><li>Koshi Barrage viewpoint for flamingo and waterfowl aggregations</li><li>Koshi Tappu Wildlife Reserve on the river's floodplain (Ramsar site)</li></ul>`,
