    name: "Koshi Tappu Wildlife Reserve",
    category: "NATIONAL_PARK",
    summary: "Koshi Tappu Wildlife Reserve is a 175 km\u00b2 Ramsar-designated wetland reserve in the Saptakoshi floodplain of eastern Terai, sheltering Nepal's last surviving herd of wild water buffalo and an extraordinary 485 bird species. Established in 1976, it encompasses seasonally flooded grasslands, reed beds, and riverine forest that provide critical habitat for waterbirds, gharial crocodiles, spotted deer, and smooth-coated otters. It is consistently ranked as one of Asia's most important freshwater wetland sites for avifauna.",
    story: `<p>Koshi Tappu Wildlife Reserve was established in 1976 to protect a critical island of biodiversity in Nepal's heavily farmed eastern Terai. The name 'Tappu' means 'island' in Nepali, referring to the way the Saptakoshi River historically bifurcated around the reserve's forested core. In 1987, UNESCO and the Ramsar Convention recognised its international importance as a wetland of global significance, and the reserve has since become the cornerstone of a larger conservation landscape extending south into India's Bihar state.</p><h3>Wild Buffalo and Wetland Ecology</h3><p>The reserve holds Nepal's only wild population of the Asian wild water buffalo (Bubalus arnee), a species classified as Endangered globally. The 2016 census recorded 432 individuals, growing at an impressive annual rate. The reserve's mosaic of grasslands, shallow wetlands, and gallery forest also supports hog deer, blue bull, wild boar, jackal, and smooth-coated otter. The Koshi River's sandbanks provide nesting sites for gharial crocodiles and Gangetic dolphins are occasionally spotted in deeper channels.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Nepal's last herd of wild water buffalo (432 individuals, 2016 census)</li><li>485 bird species including large adjutant stork, swamp francolin, Pallas's fish eagle</li><li>Ramsar Wetland of International Importance (1987)</li><li>Excellent jeep and elephant safaris through grassland and forest</li><li>Koshi River boat rides for waterbird observation</li><li>Peak birding October–March when migratory species arrive</li></ul>`,
