    category: "NATIONAL_PARK",
    summary: "Parsa National Park is a 627 km\u00b2 protected area in Nepal's south-central Terai, characterised by dense sal forest, Siwalik hill ranges, and rich wildlife including a booming Bengal tiger population that grew from 4 in 2008 to 41 in 2022. Sharing a border with Chitwan National Park to the west and India's Valmiki Tiger Reserve to the south, Parsa forms a critical wildlife corridor that supports tigers, elephants, sloth bears, leopards, and gaur. It was upgraded from Wildlife Reserve to National Park status in 2017.",
    story: `<p>Parsa's conservation story is one of Nepal's most remarkable recovery narratives. When it was first surveyed in 2008, only four Bengal tigers remained in the entire reserve. Through intensive anti-poaching efforts, community engagement, and its 2017 upgrade to National Park status, the tiger population surged to 19 by 2017 and reached 41 by 2022—a tenfold increase in fourteen years. The park's 627 square kilometres encompass the rugged Churia (Siwalik) hills rising 435–950 metres above the Terai plains, cloaked almost entirely in sal forest.</p><h3>Wildlife and Landscape</h3><p>Parsa's proximity to Chitwan and the transboundary connection with India's Valmiki Tiger Reserve means large mammals move freely across a vast landscape. Elephants traverse the hills seasonally, and the park's network of waterholes and river courses supports gharial crocodiles, Indian pythons, and a host of deer species including barasingha. Birdlife is equally impressive, with over 320 species recorded including Bengal florican, lesser adjutant, and multiple raptor species.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>41 Bengal tigers (2022) – one of Nepal's fastest-recovering tiger populations</li><li>Connected to Chitwan NP and India's Valmiki Tiger Reserve</li><li>Dense sal forest covering 90% of the park</li><li>Elephant, jeep, and walking safaris available</li><li>Less visited than Chitwan – more wilderness feel</li><li>Upgraded from Wildlife Reserve to National Park in 2017</li></ul>`,
