    name: "National Museum of Nepal",
    category: "ARCHAEOLOGICAL",
    summary: "The National Museum of Nepal at Chhauni, Kathmandu, is the country's premier repository of historical, cultural, and natural heritage, housed across three buildings at the foot of Swayambhunath Hill. Founded in 1928, its collection spans pre-historic stone tools, medieval arms and armour, royal regalia, Buddhist and Hindu sculptures, postage stamps, coins, and a notable Doll Gallery containing gifts to the royal family from heads of state. The museum's most prized possession is a sword presented by French Emperor Louis-Napoleon Bonaparte.",
    story: `<p>The National Museum of Nepal was founded in 1928 as the Shree Teen Sarkar Library and Museum under Prime Minister Chandra Shamsher Rana, initially housing royal trophies and arms. Over the following decades the collection expanded dramatically to encompass pre-historic artefacts, Hindu and Buddhist religious sculptures, and ethnographic material from across Nepal's diverse cultures. Today the museum complex comprises the Historical Museum Building, the Buddhist Art Gallery (Juddha Jayatia Kala Shala), and additional galleries for numismatics and natural history.</p><h3>The Collections</h3><p>The arms and armour gallery is one of the most visited sections, featuring khukuris, swords, shields, cane helmets, and leather cannons seized during Nepal's 1792 war with Tibet. A remarkable exhibit is a submachine gun and sword presented by Louis-Napoleon Bonaparte of France. The Buddhist Art Gallery houses gilded statues, thangka paintings, and ritual objects spanning several centuries. The Doll Gallery, a quirky but beloved section, displays dolls gifted to female royalty from world leaders and foreign dignitaries.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Founded 1928 – Nepal's oldest and largest national museum</li><li>Louis-Napoleon Bonaparte's sword – most prized artefact</li><li>Extensive arms gallery including Tibetan-war-era leather cannons</li><li>Buddhist Art Gallery with thangkas and gilded sculptures</li><li>Located near Swayambhunath Stupa – easy to combine visits</li><li>Postage stamp and coin collection gallery</li></ul>`,
