    name: "Thapathali Suspension Bridge",
    category: "ARCHAEOLOGICAL",
    summary: "The Thapathali area on the Bagmati River in central Kathmandu is historically significant as the site of Nepal's first modern bridge, originally built in 1810 under Prime Minister Bhimsen Thapa, and subsequently replaced by a 400-foot black iron suspension bridge imported from Paris and inaugurated in 1939 under Prime Minister Juddha Shamsher Rana. The bridge connects Thapathali in Kathmandu with Teku in Lalitpur across the Bagmati and remains an engineering and heritage landmark along the river. The surrounding Thapathali Durbar grounds add royal historical significance to the site.",
    story: `<p>Thapathali holds a unique place in Nepal's infrastructure history as the crossing point where the country's first engineered bridge was constructed in 1810. Commissioned by the formidable Prime Minister Bhimsen Thapa at the behest of Queen Regent Lalit Tripura Sundari, the original timber and pile structure spanned the Bagmati River at a point where the royal palace grounds of Thapathali Durbar met the southern bank. It was inaugurated in 1868 Bikram Sambat by King Girvan Yuddha Bikram Shah.</p><h3>The 1939 Iron Bridge</h3><p>The current and most celebrated structure at Thapathali is the 400-foot (approximately 120 m) black iron suspension bridge, prefabricated in Paris and shipped to Nepal under the direction of Prime Minister Juddha Shamsher Rana, who inaugurated it in March 1939. The imported French engineering was a statement of modernity by the Rana regime and represented Nepal's first significant use of European industrial infrastructure. The bridge connects Thapathali on the Kathmandu bank with Teku on the Lalitpur side, and pedestrians and cyclists still use it today.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Nepal's first bridge site – original 1810 timber structure by Bhimsen Thapa</li><li>1939 Paris-fabricated iron suspension bridge – still standing</li><li>Crosses Bagmati River between Thapathali and Teku</li><li>Adjacent to Thapathali Durbar – former royal palace grounds</li><li>Part of the Bagmati Promenade riverside heritage walk</li></ul>`,
